Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Bring @garlic herb butter{2%tablespoon} to room temperature. Wash and dry produce.

Halve @fingerling potatoes{12%ounce} lengthwise; toss on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, arrange @maple pork breakfast sausage{10%ounce} on a separate lightly oiled baking sheet. Roast on middle rack, turning sausage halfway through, until browned and cooked through, ~{15-17%minutes}.

Meanwhile, dice @gouda cheese{2%slice} into ¼-inch pieces. Halve, core, and thinly slice @granny smith apple{1}.

Heat a #medium dry pan{} over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce}; cook, turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper towel-lined plate{}. Once cool enough to handle, roughly chop.

Halve @demi-baguette{1} lengthwise and toast until golden brown. Spread cut sides with half the garlic herb butter. Slice into 1-inch strips; halve strips to create short spears.

Once potatoes and sausage are done, in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat, combine @cream sauce base{8%ounce} and @cheese roux concentrate{1%ounce}. Cook, stirring constantly, until steaming and bubbling slightly, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Reduce heat to medium. Add gouda and @white cheddar cheese{1/2%cup} one small handful at a time, alternating and whisking constantly between additions, until melted. Remove from heat; season with pepper.

Transfer roasted potatoes to a #large bowl{} and toss with remaining garlic herb butter.

Cut sausage on a diagonal into 2-inch-long pieces.

If desired, transfer fondue to a #serving bowl{}. Top fondue with chopped bacon.

Place roasted potatoes, sausage, apple slices, and baguette spears on a #large board{}. Serve family style with fondue for dipping.

> TIP: Place a trivet or kitchen towel underneath the fondue pot to protect your table.

> Pork Sausage is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 160°.

> Bacon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.